This form is represented by seven specimens, five of which are figured. Most of the speci- mens are fragmentary or poorly preserved. The general form, size, and disposition of the pinnules, however, is adequately shown in figure 6; details of the venation appear in figure 7.

In all observable features these specimens are indistinguishable from the figures and type specimens of this Laramie species. The details of the venation are somewhat better preserved than in Knowlton's specimens, indicating, as he intimated‚ that some of the finer veins are once- forked near the midvein.
